{
  "intro": {
    "title": "Quantifiers",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Quantifiers — countable vs uncountable is the key split",
        "content": "Quantifiers answer **how much?** or **how many?** They sit in the determiner slot (same as *a / the*). The biggest decision is always: is the noun **countable** (*book, friend*) or **uncountable** (*water, time, advice*)? That choice controls which quantifier is grammatical.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "groups": [
              {
                "label": "Countable only",
                "items": [
                  "many",
                  "few",
                  "a few",
                  "both",
                  "either",
                  "neither"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "Uncountable only",
                "items": [
                  "much",
                  "little",
                  "a little"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "Both",
                "items": [
                  "some",
                  "any",
                  "a lot of",
                  "lots of",
                  "all",
                  "most",
                  "no",
                  "enough"
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "style": "cz",
            "text": "Czech drops determiners freely (*Mám mléko.*). English usually needs *some* or *any* with plural or uncountable nouns — omitting them sounds like a beginner."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      },
      {
        "title": "some / any",
        "content": "**The default pair** — both mean an unspecified amount. They work with countable and uncountable nouns.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "some vs any",
            "headers": [
              "Word",
              "Use in",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**some**",
                "Positive statements, offers and requests",
                "I have **some** milk. Would you like **some** tea?"
              ],
              [
                "**any**",
                "Negatives and questions",
                "I don't have **any** money. Do you have **any** time?"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "I bought some bread.",
                "why": "positive → some"
              },
              {
                "good": "I didn't buy any bread.",
                "why": "negative → any"
              },
              {
                "good": "Did you buy any bread?",
                "why": "genuine question → any"
              },
              {
                "good": "Would you like some bread?",
                "why": "offer (expecting yes) → some"
              },
              {
                "bad": "I have any milk.",
                "good": "I have some milk.",
                "why": "positive statement → some"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      },
      {
        "title": "much / many / a lot of — and (a) few / (a) little",
        "content": "**Large amounts**: *much* (uncountable), *many* (countable), *a lot of* (both — the natural choice in positive statements).\n**Small amounts**: *a few* (countable, positive), *few* (countable, negative), *a little* (uncountable, positive), *little* (uncountable, negative).\n\n**The *a* makes all the difference**: *a few friends* = some (positive); *few friends* = almost none (negative — lonely). Same flip with *a little* vs *little*.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "Amount quantifiers",
            "headers": [
              "Word",
              "Countable / Uncountable",
              "Feeling",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**many**",
                "Countable",
                "Neutral",
                "many books, not many seats"
              ],
              [
                "**much**",
                "Uncountable",
                "Negative/questions (avoid in positives)",
                "not much time, how much money?"
              ],
              [
                "**a lot of**",
                "Both",
                "Neutral (natural in positives)",
                "a lot of friends, a lot of water"
              ],
              [
                "**a few**",
                "Countable",
                "Positive (some)",
                "I have a few friends — enough"
              ],
              [
                "**few**",
                "Countable",
                "Negative (almost none)",
                "He has few friends — lonely"
              ],
              [
                "**a little**",
                "Uncountable",
                "Positive (some)",
                "I need a little help"
              ],
              [
                "**little**",
                "Uncountable",
                "Negative (almost none)",
                "There's little hope — bleak"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "bad": "I have much friends.",
                "good": "I have a lot of friends.",
                "why": "countable + positive → a lot of, not much"
              },
              {
                "bad": "I have few time.",
                "good": "I have a little time.",
                "why": "time is uncountable; a little = some (positive)"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A2.quantifiers.much_many_a_lot",
          "A2.quantifiers.few_little"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A2"
      },
      {
        "title": "all / most / no / none — and both / either / neither",
        "content": "**The degree scale** (100% → 0%) and the **exactly-two** group:",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "Degree scale",
            "headers": [
              "Word",
              "Meaning",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**all**",
                "100%",
                "All students passed. All the water is gone."
              ],
              [
                "**most**",
                "Majority",
                "Most people agree. Most of the time it works."
              ],
              [
                "**no** + noun",
                "Zero (before noun)",
                "I have no time. There are no seats."
              ],
              [
                "**none** / **none of**",
                "Zero (no noun after)",
                "None of them came. How many left? None."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "Exactly two things",
            "headers": [
              "Word",
              "Meaning",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**both**",
                "The two together (plural verb)",
                "Both answers are correct."
              ],
              [
                "**either**",
                "One or the other",
                "You can sit on either side."
              ],
              [
                "**neither**",
                "Not one and not the other (singular verb)",
                "Neither answer is right."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "bad": "None students came.",
                "good": "No students came. / None of the students came.",
                "why": "no + noun; none + of the + noun"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B1.quantifiers.all_most_none"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B1"
      },
      {
        "title": "Common errors + roadmap",
        "content": "**Next steps**: For the noun side — when a noun is countable vs uncountable in the first place — see [[topic:countable_uncountable|Countable & Uncountable Nouns]]. For the determiner slot more broadly, see [[topic:articles|Articles (a/an/the)]].",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "title": "High-frequency Czech-speaker errors",
            "items": [
              {
                "bad": "much friends",
                "good": "a lot of friends",
                "why": "countable + positive → a lot of"
              },
              {
                "bad": "many water",
                "good": "much / a lot of water",
                "why": "water is uncountable"
              },
              {
                "bad": "I have few time.",
                "good": "I have a little time.",
                "why": "time is uncountable; a little = some (positive)"
              },
              {
                "bad": "I have any money.",
                "good": "I have some money.",
                "why": "positive → some"
              },
              {
                "bad": "None students came.",
                "good": "No students came.",
                "why": "no + noun"
              },
              {
                "bad": "less people",
                "good": "fewer people",
                "why": "countable → fewer; uncountable → less"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any",
          "A2.quantifiers.much_many_a_lot",
          "A2.quantifiers.few_little",
          "B1.quantifiers.all_most_none"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A2"
      }
    ]
  },
  "check": {
    "title": "Test your understanding",
    "questions": [
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'I have _____ milk.' (positive) Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "some",
          "b": "any",
          "c": "much",
          "d": "many"
        },
        "correct_option": "a",
        "explanation": "Positive statement with uncountable → some."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'How _____ books did you read?' Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "much",
          "b": "many",
          "c": "some",
          "d": "little"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Books = countable → many."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'She has _____ friends.' (a small number, positive) Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "few",
          "b": "a few",
          "c": "little",
          "d": "a little"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Friends = countable; positive (some) → a few."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'There isn't _____ time.' Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "some",
          "b": "any",
          "c": "many",
          "d": "few"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Negative → any."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'I need _____ help.' (a small amount, positive) Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "little",
          "b": "a little",
          "c": "few",
          "d": "a few"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Help = uncountable; positive → a little."
      }
    ]
  },
